body:
{{champion:50}} : &quot;She claimed it was the Frost Queen&#039;s grave. They believed her.&quot;

{{champion:44}}  &quot;That bow is of the stars, as is its mistress.&quot;

So we know Ashe lied about finding the bow at the Avarosas&#039; cairn from Swains&#039; secret knowing demon. Her story of being chased by bandits into a random clearing where she magically finds the burial site of one of the most revered heroes of the Freljord that she just happens to be a descendant of is baloney.

But Taric tells us more &quot;That bow is of the stars&quot; he&#039;s talking about Targon? (I&#039;m certain the &#039;as it&#039;s mistress&#039; part is just him macking on Ashe)The enemy of Targon is the Void but there still is no connection to the Freljord there. Until you remember that the Watchers are the masters of the Void. They want Ashe on their side so they can take the fight to Targon after she unites the Freljord perhaps? Thus they promised her power in return for her loyalty. Maybe they want to create more &quot;Iceborn&quot; (to me this means nothing more than Void-infected northerners, basically the Freljordian version of Shurimas&#039; Ascended or Mount Targons&#039; Aspects but champions that represent the Void) but the Watchers think Ashe would be more useful than {{champion:127}}, as despite her continued loyalty she has already failed to protect them once before and maybe they have lost all confidence in her (which is tragic considering that her only motivation is to bring the Watchers back as she was the only one appreciated their &quot;gifts&quot; where Avarosa and Serylda didn&#039;t).

{{champion:223}} s&#039; quotes reveal more. For those who don&#039;t know Kench has Ally and Enemy voice lines for most of the champs he interacts with. In the Ally voice lines he tells them what they want to hear so that they will take his deal and probably get consumed once they trust him and his honeyed wordsif they are on the enemy team he doesn&#039;t waste words and instead chides them knowing he can&#039;t manipulate them into becoming his dinner.

Ally: &quot;If you wanna&#039; build an empire of peace, then your mortar will be blood.&quot; This might reflect Ashe&#039;s mindset. Her mother was killed by the constant warring in the Freljord so it&#039;s natural that she hates the neverending strife between tribes. She knows she can&#039;t undo it in one life time which is why she turned to Watchers for help who gave her the bow that would inspire people to follow her (Ashe isn&#039;t a natural leader her short bio reads &quot;Stoic, intelligent, and idealistic, yet uncomfortable with her role as leader&quot;) in return for a united Freljordian army who could be turned into a 2nd generation of Iceborn slaves. Tahm is trying to appeal to her rationale to get closer to her.

Enemy: &quot;Girl, you got as much &#039;foresight&#039; as a blindfolded mole.&quot;, outside of the context of my theory this quote doesn&#039;t make any sense. Like I said Kench tells his teammates what they want to hear and his enemies the cold truth.

Enemy {{champion:114}} &quot;A duel is a fight between two imbeciles... and you are the greatest.&quot;
Enemy {{champion:32}} &quot;I say, you&#039;re as &#039;fun&#039; as a leaky roof.&quot;
Enemy {{champion:41}} &quot;Your attempt to be monstrous is as successful as your dictatorship.&quot;

So why is he bringing up Ashes&#039; &quot;foresight&quot;? She isn&#039;t really known for having a flaw that comes from lacking foresight. Unless you consider the possibility that she is LYING to her people and Tahm Kench is insinuating that this lie will come back to bite her one day.

This puts everything into focus: her marriage to {{champion:23}} despite him being the epitomy of everything she resents a brutish warrior that prides himself on being able to kill anyone ({{champion:266}} notwithstanding ofc) She bit the bullet and married him anyway to reach her goal of uniting the Freljord despite the fact that she probably despises Trynd.

So many questions. How is {{champion:201}} involved if the popular theory of him being a Watcher/Iceborn in disguise are true. Did he lead her to the bow? Serve as an inbetween for the Watchers? Their emissary?

Guess we may find out more when {{champion:20}} drops and we get more lore on the subject.

I really like the implications of this wrinkle. Before Ashe was the shining hero that completely invalidated {{champion:113}} and {{champion:127}} claims. Now I&#039;m not so sure.
